{"ts": "2026-06-09T18:02:27.637339+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Labels can't be set with the current token scope. Let me add a triage comment instead:", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 412, "prompt_tokens": 12838, "total_tokens": 13250, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 18, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 12352}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "mimo-v2.5-pro", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "beb700eb97214552b038c5f7e51a56f3", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ead8c-9b88-79a2-9922-3378415ea62f-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A01", "issue_number": 1, "body": "**Triage: Confirmed bug.** Thank you for the report, @BruceKZ.\n\nI've verified the issue against the current codebase:\n\n1. **`scripts/apply_migrations.sh`** (line 16) uses a bare `for f in migrations/*.sql` loop with no explicit sort. The script's own comment acknowledges it \"relies on shell glob expansion ordering.\"\n\n2. **The migration files** (`001_create_users.sql`, `002_create_sessions.sql`, `003_add_session_index.sql`) have a clear dependency chain — `003` creates an index on the `sessions` table defined in `002`.\n\n3. **On case-folding filesystems** (APFS default, NTFS, etc.), the glob order is locale-dependent (`LC_COLLATE`), which can reorder the expansion and break the intended sequence.\n\n**Recommended fix** — sort the glob explicitly before iterating:\n\n```bash\nfor f in $(printf '%s\\n' migrations/*.sql | sort); do\n```\n\nor equivalently:\n\n```bash\nfor f in $(ls migrations/*.sql | sort); do\n```\n\nThis ensures lexicographic ordering regardless of the host filesystem's collation behavior.\